---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout title="About — realpls" description="Learn what realpls does, how the forensic checks work, and their limitations.">
  <Header />
  
  <main class="main container container-narrow">
    <article class="content">
      <header class="content-header">
        <h1>About realpls</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          A lightweight, browser-based tool for quick image authenticity checks.
          No uploads, no AI, no magic — just practical forensic heuristics.
        </p>
      </header>
      
      <section class="section">
        <h2>What this tool does</h2>
        <p>
          realpls runs a series of forensic checks on images to help identify potential signs of manipulation. 
          These checks analyze metadata, compression artifacts, and pixel-level patterns that may indicate editing.
        </p>
        <p>
          All processing happens entirely in your browser. Your images never leave your device, and there's 
          no server-side component involved in the analysis.
        </p>
      </section>
      
      <section class="section">
        <h2>What this tool does NOT do</h2>
        <div class="warning-box">
          <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
            <path d="M12 9v2m0 4h.01M12 3l9.196 15H2.804L12 3z" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
          <div>
            <p><strong>This is not a lie detector for images.</strong></p>
            <p>
              realpls cannot definitively prove whether an image is "real" or "fake." No tool can do this 
              with certainty. The checks here provide signals that may warrant further investigation, but 
              they are not conclusive evidence of manipulation.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <ul class="list">
          <li><strong>No AI/ML detection</strong> — We don't use machine learning models to detect AI-generated images</li>
          <li><strong>No deepfake detection</strong> — This tool cannot identify synthetic faces or AI-generated content</li>
          <li><strong>Not forensically admissible</strong> — Results should not be used as legal evidence</li>
          <li><strong>No absolute certainty</strong> — Every check has limitations and false positive/negative rates</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
      
      <section class="section">
        <h2>The Checks</h2>
        <p>
          Here's an overview of each forensic check, what it looks for, and its limitations:
        </p>
        
        <div class="check-explainer">
          <h3>File Type Detection</h3>
          <p>
            Verifies the actual file format by reading the first bytes (magic numbers) and comparing with 
            the declared file type and extension.
          </p>
          <p class="limitation">
            <strong>Limitations:</strong> A mismatch doesn't necessarily indicate manipulation — files can be 
            renamed legitimately. Conversely, a match doesn't prove authenticity.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="check-explainer">
          <h3>EXIF Metadata Analysis</h3>
          <p>
            Extracts and analyzes EXIF data including camera make/model, software tags, timestamps, and GPS 
            coordinates. Flags known editing software signatures.
          </p>
          <p class="limitation">
            <strong>Limitations:</strong> EXIF can be easily modified, copied, or stripped. Missing EXIF is 
            extremely common after social media sharing and doesn't indicate manipulation. Presence of editing 
            software in metadata doesn't mean malicious editing occurred — photographers commonly use editing software.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="check-explainer">
          <h3>JPEG Quality Estimation</h3>
          <p>
            Analyzes the JPEG quantization tables to estimate the compression quality level used when saving.
          </p>
          <p class="limitation">
            <strong>Limitations:</strong> This is a rough estimate only. Low quality doesn't indicate manipulation — 
            it's common for web images. Different encoders produce different tables at the same "quality" setting.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="check-explainer">
          <h3>Block Boundary Analysis</h3>
          <p>
            Examines 8×8 pixel block boundaries characteristic of JPEG compression. Unusual patterns may suggest 
            recompression or editing.
          </p>
          <p class="limitation">
            <strong>Limitations:</strong> Marked as experimental. Strong block boundaries occur naturally in 
            lower-quality JPEGs. Many false positives possible. Results should be interpreted with extreme caution.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="check-explainer">
          <h3>Noise Consistency Analysis</h3>
          <p>
            Analyzes texture/noise patterns across the image using Laplacian filtering. Regions with significantly 
            different noise characteristics may indicate compositing.
          </p>
          <p class="limitation">
            <strong>Limitations:</strong> Natural images often have varying noise levels (e.g., sky vs. foliage). 
            JPEG compression also affects noise distribution. High sensitivity leads to false positives on 
            legitimate images.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="check-explainer">
          <h3>Edge Analysis</h3>
          <p>
            Detects edge strength throughout the image. Unusually sharp edges around specific regions might 
            indicate cut-and-paste operations.
          </p>
          <p class="limitation">
            <strong>Limitations:</strong> Sharp edges are common in high-contrast photos, text, graphics, 
            and many legitimate image types. This check has a high false positive rate.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="check-explainer">
          <h3>Clone Detection</h3>
          <p>
            Uses block hashing to find repeated regions that are spatially separated, which might indicate 
            copy-paste editing (clone stamp tool).
          </p>
          <p class="limitation">
            <strong>Limitations:</strong> Patterns, textures, and naturally repeating elements cause false 
            positives. The "quick" scan uses larger blocks and may miss subtle cloning. Even the "deep scan" 
            cannot detect all types of cloning.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="check-explainer">
          <h3>Error Level Analysis (ELA)</h3>
          <p>
            Re-encodes the image as JPEG and compares error levels. Areas that have been modified more recently 
            may show different error levels.
          </p>
          <p class="limitation">
            <strong>Limitations:</strong> ELA is notorious for producing misleading results. Multiple resaves, 
            social media reuploads, and different content types (text vs. photos) all affect ELA results. 
            This check is informational only and should never be used as evidence of manipulation.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="check-explainer">
          <h3>Social Media Detection</h3>
          <p>
            Looks for patterns common in social media reuploads: missing EXIF, specific dimension limits, 
            and recompression artifacts.
          </p>
          <p class="limitation">
            <strong>Limitations:</strong> This is purely informational and does not indicate manipulation. 
            Many legitimate images pass through social media. False positives and negatives are common.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
      
      <section class="section">
        <h2>Best Practices</h2>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Use multiple signals together — no single check is conclusive</li>
          <li>Consider the image's history and context</li>
          <li>Remember that sophisticated edits may evade all these checks</li>
          <li>When in doubt, consult a professional forensic analyst</li>
          <li>Never make accusations based solely on these results</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
      
      <section class="section">
        <h2>Technical Details</h2>
        <p>
          realpls is built with Astro and TypeScript, running entirely in the browser using standard web APIs 
          (Canvas, FileReader, ImageData). For EXIF parsing, we use the 
          <a href="https://github.com/MikeKovaworker/exifr" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">exifr</a> 
          library.
        </p>
        <p>
          The source code is designed to be readable and educational. Each check module explains its approach 
          and limitations in comments.
        </p>
      </section>
      
      <div class="back-link">
        <a href="/">← Back to analyzer</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
  
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .main {
    flex: 1;
    padding-top: var(--space-10);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-10);
  }
  
  .content {
    background: var(--color-bg-elevated);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-xl);
    padding: var(--space-10);
  }
  
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .content {
      padding: var(--space-6);
    }
  }
  
  .content-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-10);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-8);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }
  
  .content-header h1 {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }
  
  .lead {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
  }
  
  .section {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-10);
  }
  
  .section h2 {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }
  
  .section p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
  }
  
  .warning-box {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-4);
    background: var(--color-warn-bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-warn);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }
  
  .warning-box svg {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    color: var(--color-warn);
  }
  
  .warning-box p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }
  
  .warning-box p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  
  .list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
  }
  
  .list li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
  }
  
  .list li::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0.6em;
    width: 6px;
    height: 6px;
    background: var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: 50%;
  }
  
  .check-explainer {
    padding: var(--space-5);
    background: var(--color-bg-subtle);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }
  
  .check-explainer h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }
  
  .check-explainer p {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }
  
  .check-explainer p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  
  .limitation {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  
  .limitation strong {
    font-style: normal;
  }
  
  .back-link {
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    padding-top: var(--space-6);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }
  
  .back-link a {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-2);
    font-weight: 500;
  }
</style>

